cQueen |editor2-first=Fiona |editor3-last=Pnacekova |editor3-first=Michaela |editor4-last=Sahli |editor4-first=Sabrina |title=Examining Aspects of Sexualities and the Self |date=2010 |publisher=Inter-Disciplinary Press |location=Oxford |isbn=978-1-84888-020-7 |pages=3-20 |url=http://www.inter-disciplinary.net/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/PaS6ever3150410.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120904074417/http://www.inter-disciplinary.net/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/PaS6ever3150410.pdf |archivedate=4 September 2012 |chapter=Specifics of the Contemporary Czech Homosexual Community: History, Evolution and Ambivalences}}\n*{{cite magazine |ref=harv |last1=Vodr\u00e1\u017eka |first1=Mirek |title=\u010cesk\u00e9 prost\u0159ed\u00ed m\u011b neinspiruje |magazine=TaGitaCZ |date=17 August 2009 |url=http://www.ta-gita.cz:80/kriticke-reflexe/ceske-prostredi-me-neinspiruje/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |trans-title=The Czech Environment Did Not Inspire Me |publisher=Projekt gitAEvropa |location=Prague |language=Czech |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091031130650/http://www.ta-gita.cz:80/kriticke-reflexe/ceske-prostredi-me-neinspiruje/ |archivedate=31 October 2009 |issn=1802-3894}}\n*{{cite web |ref={{harvid|Comparative History of Ideas Department |2014}} |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=CHID Study Abroad Program in Prague: Vera Sokolova |url=http://www.chidprague.cz/index.php?x=people&y=1&a=sokolova&b=1&z=5 |website=Comparative History of Ideas Department |publisher=[[University of Washington]] |accessdate=1 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413072953/http://www.chidprague.cz/index.php?x=people&y=1&a=sokolova&b=1&z=5 |archivedate=13 April 2017 |location=Seattle, Washington  |date=2014}}\n*{{cite web |ref={{harvid|Deutsche National Bibliothek|2020}} |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=Katalog der Deutschen Nationalbibliothek: Sokolov\u00e1, V\u011bra |url=https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&cqlMode=true&query=nid%3D136164803 |publisher=Deutsche National Bibliothek |accessdate=1 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401181558/https://portal.dnb.de/opac.htm?method=simpleSearch&cqlMode=true&query=nid%3D136164803 |archivedate=1 April 2020 |location=Leipzig |language=German |date=13 February 2020 |trans-title=Catalog of the German National Library: Sokolov\u00e1, V\u011bra}}\n*{{cite web |ref={{harvid|Charles University|2015}} |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=O n\u00e1s: Publikace katedry |url=https://gender.fhs.cuni.cz/KGS-4.html |website=Fakulta humanitn\u00edch studi\u00ed |publisher=[[Charles University]] |accessdate=1 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819195522/https://gender.fhs.cuni.cz/KGS-4.html |archivedate=19 August 2017 |location=Prague |language=Czech |date=2015 |trans-title=About Us: Department publications}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sokolova, Vera}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Prague]]\n[[Category:Charles University in Prague alumni]]\n[[Category:California State University, Sacramento alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Washington alumni]]\n[[Category:Charles University in Prague faculty]]\n[[Category:Czech women scientists]]\n[[Category:Czech historians]]\n[[Category:Czech sociologists]]\n[[Category:Gender studies academics]]\n[[Category:21st-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century social scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century historians]]\n[[Category:Women historians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{for| the Russian race walker|Vera Sokolova}}\n'''V\u011bra Sokolov\u00e1''' (born 1970) is a Czech academic who specializes in [[gender studies]] and specifically focuses on identity policy and the construction of sexuality from a historical and social perspective, evaluating the power, structuring and defining of sexuality to transcend binary boundaries. She is the chair of the Department of Gender Studies at [[Charles University]] in Prague. She is the co-managing editor of ''Gender and Generation'', along with Kate\u0159ina Kol\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1.\n\n==Biography==\nV\u011bra Sokolov\u00e1 was born in Czechoslovakia in 1970.{{sfn|Deutsche National Bibliothek|2020}} She earned a [[bachelor of science]] degree in geography at [[Charles University]] in 1992, before continuing her studies in the United States at [[California State University, Sacramento|California State University]] in Sacramento.{{sfn|Comparative History of Ideas Department|2014}} In the U. S., she studied history and cultural anthropology.{{sfn|Cerqueirov\u00e1|2004}} After graduating ''[[summa cum laude]]'' with a [[bachelor of arts]] degree in history in 1994, she completed a [[master's degree]] (1996) and a PhD in history at the [[University of Washington]] (2002).{{sfn|Comparative History of Ideas Department|2014}} Sokolov\u00e1 was one of the pioneering academics of gender studies in the Czech Republic, beginning to teach the subject before it was an accredited field in the country. She inaugurated the Queer Studies course in the arts faculty of Charles University in 2001.{{sfn|Hlup\u00e1|2003}} Since 2003 she has been the chair of the Department of Gender Studies in the Humanities Faculty of Charles University{{sfn|Comparative History of Ideas Department|2014}} and is the co-managing editor of the academic journal ''Gender and Generation'' of the department.{{sfn|Charles University|2015}}{{sfn|Havelkov\u00e1|Oates-Indruchov\u00e1|2014|p=x}} She has lectured abroad at the [[New School University]] in New York City, Baltimore's [[University of Maryland]] and the University of Washington.{{sfn|Hlup\u00e1|2003}} She also is a member of the Czech Republics Government Council's Committee for Sexual Minorities.{{sfn|Havelkov\u00e1|Oates-Indruchov\u00e1|2014|p=x}}\n\nSokolov\u00e1's research interests lie in the development of the idea of gender and its historic constructs in society. She has studied the history of the discipline, as it moved from women's studies, to feminist studies, and finally gender studies and is interested in the way that the definition of gender effects power relationships in society.{{sfn|Vodr\u00e1\u017eka|2009}} She has evaluated how feminist movements were different in Western and socialist countries, in that rather than a political movement, the state took over the mechanisms to modernize women's status in the East.{{sfn|Li\u0161kov\u00e1|2018|p=3}} She has analyzed the impact of the development of ethnic and gender studies on governmental policy. For example, under communism, [[Romani people|Roma]] ethnic groups were treated as deviant, but launching programs to reignite the study of the Romani people's ethnicity in the 1970s amplified their differences and escalated discrimination in society.{{sfn|Hegburg|2012|p=227}}{{sfn|Albert|Szilvasi|2017|p=26}} \nIn her studies on policy, Sokolov\u00e1 has shown that officials arbitrarily applied policy, based on ethnicity and gender. During the state socialist period, the national policy to increase births did not allow Czech and Slovak women to have abortions. Simultaneously a policy of forced sterilization was implemented on Romani women{{sfn|Bren|2010|p=168}} in an effort to correct falling birth rates among Czech and Slovak women.{{sfn|Albert|Szilvasi|2017|p=26}} \n\nAccording to Sokolov\u00e1, the invisibility of non-heterosexual lives in the Soviet period was erased with the birth of gender studies. Identification of homosexuals and lesbians created a consequence that they might be seen as criminals{{sfn|Li\u0161kov\u00e1|2018|pp=233\u2013234}} and hardened hetero-normative and binary definitions of society.{{sfn|Havelkov\u00e1|Oates-Indruchov\u00e1|2014|p=253}} She found that women's studies programs, or the interpretation of feminism projected to the country from Czech exiles living abroad, like [[Josef \u0160kvoreck\u00fd]],{{sfn|Cerqueirov\u00e1|2004}} created a disregard or anti-feminist reaction in the Czech Republic. This included lesbians, who were doubly discriminated against as women by society at large and as queer by the homosexual community.{{sfn|Sloboda|2010|p=5}} The Queer Studies course she launched at Charles University focuses on a critical analysis of how sexuality is used as a means of social control.{{sfn|Hlup\u00e1|2003}} She has been involved in the state television program for the LGBT community, known as ''Queer'' (formerly called ''LeGaTo'') since it began airing in 2004{{sfn|Cerqueirov\u00e1|2004}}{{sfn|Kulpa|Mizielinska|2016|p=132}} and participates in community activism on both a cultural and political level.{{sfn|Hlup\u00e1|2003}}\n\n==Selected works==\n*{{cite book |last=Sokolov\u00e1 |first=V\u011bra |editor-last1=Isaacs |editor-first1=Ann Katherine |title=Political Systems and Definitions of Gender Roles |date=2001 |publisher=Edizioni Plus, Universit\u00e0 di Pisa |location=Pisa |isbn=978-88-8492-072-0 |chapter=Representations of Homosexuality and the Separation of Gender and Sexuality in the Czech Republic Before and After 1989 |pages=273\u2013288}}\n*{{cite book |last=Sokolov\u00e1 |first=V\u011bra |editor-last1=Forrester |editor-first1=Sibelan |editor-last2=Zaborowska |editor-first2=Magdalena J. |editor-last3=Gapova |editor-first3=Elena |title=Over the Wall/After the Fall: Post-Communist Cultures through an East-West Gaze |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WBxskEjDtkQC&pg=PA251 |date=2004 |publisher=[[Indiana University Press]] |location=Bloomington, Indiana |isbn=0-253-11035-1 |chapter='Don't Get Pricked!' Representation and the Politics of Sexuality in the Czech Republic |pages=251-268}}\n*{{cite book |last=Sokolov\u00e1 |first=V\u011bra |editor-last1=Leeuwen-Turnovcov\u00e1 |editor-first1=Ji\u0159ina van |editor-last2=Richter |editor-first2=Nicole |title=Mediale Welten in Tschechien nach 1989: Genderprojektionen und Codes des Plebejismus |year=2005 |publisher=Verlag Otto Sagner |location=M\u00fcnchen |isbn=978-3-87690-896-0 |chapter=Identity Politics and the (B)orders of Heterosexism: Lesbians, Gays and Feminists in the Czech Media after 1989 |pages=29\u201344}}\n*{{cite book |last=Sokolov\u00e1 |first=V\u011bra |title=Cultural Politics of Ethnicity: Discourses on Roma in Communist Czechoslovakia |year=2008 |publisher=Ibidem-Verlag |location=Stuttgart, Germany |isbn=978-3-89821-864-1}}\n*{{cite book |last=Sokolov\u00e1 |first=V\u011bra |editor-last1=Hall |editor-first1=Timothy McCajor |editor-last2=Read |editor-first2=Rosie |title=Changes in the Heart of Europe: Recent Ethnographies of Czechs, Slovaks, Roma, and Sorbs |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qYk0DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA227 |year=2012 |publisher=ibidem Verlag |location=Stuttgart |isbn=978-3-8382-5606-1 |chapter=Planned Parenthood behind the Curtain: Population Policy and Sterilization of Romani Women in Communist Czechoslovakia, 1972-1989 |pages=139-172}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Sokolov\u00e1 |first1=V\u011bra |editor-last1=Havelkov\u00e1 |editor-first1=Hana |editor-last2=Oates-Indruchov\u00e1 |editor-first2=Libora |title=The Politics of Gender Culture under State Socialism: An Expropriated Voice |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A03IAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA253 |date=2014 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |isbn=978-1-317-81908-0 |chapter=State Approaches to Homosexuality and Non-heterosexual Lives in Czechoslovakia during State Socialism |pages=82-108}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Sokolov\u00e1 |first1=V\u011bra |title=Queer Encounters with Communist Power : Non-Heterosexual Lives and the State in Czechoslovakia, 1948\u20131989 |date=2020 |publisher=[[Karolinum Press]] |location=Prague |isbn=978-80-246-4266-6}}\n\n== References ==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv |last1=Albert |first1=Gwendolyn |last2=Szilvasi |first2=Marek |title=Intersectional Discrimination of Romani Women Forcibly Sterilized in the Former Czechoslovakia and Czech Republ