{"title_page": "Gouverneur Street Ferry", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[Image:1847 Lower Manhattan map.jpg|thumb|right|Map from 1847 showing the route of what was then the Navy Yard Ferry]]\nThe '''Gouverneur Street Ferry''' was a [[ferry]] route connecting [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], with the city of [[Brooklyn]], by joining Manhattan's Gouverneur Street to Brooklyn's Bridge Street across the [[East River]].\n\n==History==\nThe ferry, originally the '''Walnut Street Ferry''' and later the '''Jackson Street Ferry''' or '''Hudson Avenue Ferry''', was established on December 1, 1817.  The route originally connected Manhattan's Walnut Street (now called Jackson Street, just west of [[Lower East Side#Corlears Hook|Corlear's Hook]]) with Brooklyn's Little Street (later named Jackson Street, just east of today's Hudson Avenue and west of the [[Brooklyn Navy Yard]]).<ref name=LI>Nathaniel Scudder Prime, [https://books.google.com/books?vid=OCLC01236721&id=elEOAAAAIAAJ A History of Long Island: from its first settlement by Europeans, to the year 1845], pages 376 to 380</ref><!--when was it moved to Hudson?--> At some point, the Manhattan landing was moved two blocks west, to Gouverneur Street, driving the name change to Gouverneur Street Ferry.<!--after 8/13/47 page 2-->\n\n[[Cyrus P. Smith#Smith & Bulkley|Smith & Bulkley]] gained control by May 1852,<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=The Hudson Avenue Ferry|date = May 1, 1852|page=2}}</ref> and, effective May 23, 1853, the Brooklyn side was moved two blocks west, from Hudson Avenue to Bridge Street.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=Catharine and Bridge Street Ferries|date = May 23, 1853|page=2}}</ref> Being unable to compete with the one-cent fare adopted by the [[Brooklyn Union Ferry Company]] in November 1850, it was sold to the new [[Union Ferry Company of Brooklyn]] (the successor to the Brooklyn Union) in December 1853.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=Brooklyn Ferries|date = December 10, 1853|page=2}}</ref> The lease expired on September 12, 1856, but the company continued to operate the ferry. They petitioned the [[City of New York]] to abandon the [[Roosevelt Street Ferry]], in exchange for continuing Gouverneur Street operations and expanding the Manhattan landing.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=The Union Ferry Company|date = November 18, 1856|page=2}}</ref> The city refused, and operations ended in January 1857.<ref name=BDE>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=Brooklyn Ferries|date = July 18, 1870|page=2}}</ref>\n\nA new ferry, known as the '''Navy Yard Ferry''' or '''Hudson Avenue Ferry''', was established on July 8, 1859 between Jackson Street in Manhattan and Hudson Avenue in Brooklyn, almost exactly where the original Walnut Street Ferry ran in 1817.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=A New Ferry|date = July 9, 1859|page=3}}</ref> The [[Hudson Avenue Railroad]] opened a [[streetcar line]] from the ferry to [[Prospect Park, Brooklyn|Prospect Park]] in late 1867.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |date = December 12, 1867|page=2}}</ref> The ferry shut down in early June 1868,<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=Common Council Committees - Docks and Railroads|date = June 19, 1868|page=2}}</ref><!--this says the ferry ran from Hudson Avenue to Gouverneur Street!?--> leading the railroad to move its line to the [[Bridge Street Ferry]].<ref>[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]], Travel, August 18, 1868, page 1</ref><ref name=BDE/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:East River]]\n[[Category:Ferries of New York City]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:1847 Lower Manhattan map.jpg|thumb|right|Map from 1847 showing the route of what was then the Navy Yard Ferry]]\nThe '''Gouverneur Street Ferry''' was a [[ferry]] route connecting [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], with the city of [[Brooklyn]], by joining Manhattan's Gouverneur Street to Brooklyn's Bridge Street across the [[East River]].\n\n==History==\nThe ferry, originally the '''Walnut Street Ferry''' and later the '''Jackson Street Ferry''' or '''Hudson Avenue Ferry''', was established on December 1, 1817.  The route originally connected Manhattan's Walnut Street (now called Jackson Street, just west of [[Lower East Side#Corlears Hook|Corlear's Hook]]) with Brooklyn's Little Street (later named Jackson Street, just east of today's Hudson Avenue and west of the [[Brooklyn Navy Yard]]).<ref name=LI>Nathaniel Scudder Prime, [https://books.google.com/books?vid=OCLC01236721&id=elEOAAAAIAAJ A History of Long Island: from its first settlement by Europeans, to the year 1845], pages 376 to 380</ref><!--when was it moved to Hudson?--> At some point, the Manhattan landing was moved two blocks west, to Gouverneur Street, driving the name change to Gouverneur Street Ferry.<!--after 8/13/47 page 2-->\n\n[[Cyrus P. Smith#Smith & Bulkley|Smith & Bulkley]] gained control by May 1852,<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=The Hudson Avenue Ferry|date = 1 May 1852|page=2}}</ref> and, effective May 23, 1853, the Brooklyn side was moved two blocks west, from Hudson Avenue to Bridge Street.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=Catharine and Bridge Street Ferries|date = 23 May 1853|page=2}}</ref> Being unable to compete with the one-cent fare adopted by the [[Brooklyn Union Ferry Company]] in November 1850, it was sold to the new [[Union Ferry Company of Brooklyn]] (the successor to the Brooklyn Union) in December 1853.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=Brooklyn Ferries|date = 10 December 1853|page=2}}</ref> The lease expired on September 12, 1856, but the company continued to operate the ferry. They petitioned the [[City of New York]] to abandon the [[Roosevelt Street Ferry]], in exchange for continuing Gouverneur Street operations and expanding the Manhattan landing.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=The Union Ferry Company|date = 18 November 1856|page=2}}</ref> The city refused, and operations ended in January 1857.<ref name=BDE>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=Brooklyn Ferries|date = 18 July 1870|page=2}}</ref>\n\nA new ferry, known as the '''Navy Yard Ferry''' or '''Hudson Avenue Ferry''', was established on July 8, 1859 between Jackson Street in Manhattan and Hudson Avenue in Brooklyn, almost exactly where the original Walnut Street Ferry ran in 1817.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=A New Ferry|date = 9 July 1859|page=3}}</ref> The [[Hudson Avenue Railroad]] opened a [[streetcar line]] from the ferry to [[Prospect Park, Brooklyn|Prospect Park]] in late 1867.<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |date = 12 December 1867|page=2}}</ref> The ferry shut down in early June 1868,<ref>{{cite news | work = [[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]] | location = [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, NY]] | url = |title=Common Council Committees - Docks and Railroads|date = 19 June 1868|page=2}}</ref><!--this says the ferry ran from Hudson Avenue to Gouverneur Street!?--> leading the railroad to move its line to the [[Bridge Street Ferry]].<ref>[[Brooklyn Daily Eagle]], Travel, August 18, 1868, page 1</ref><ref name=BDE/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:East River]]\n[[Category:Ferries of New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Kew Gardens 613", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gouverneur_Street_Ferry"}
{"title_page": "Kevin Cross", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish barrister, High Court judge since 2011}}\n{{Infobox judge\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable|The Hon. Mr. Justice]]\n| name             = Kevin Cross\n| image            =\n| office           = Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]]\n| term_start       = 24 October 2011\n| term_end         = \n| nominator        = [[Government of the 31st D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer        = [[Mary McAleese]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth year and age|1951}}\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party            = \n| spouse           = Alison Lindsay\n| children         =\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = {{Ubl|[[University College Dublin]]|[[King's Inns]]}}\n| signature        = \n|}}\n\n'''Kevin Cross''' (born 1951<ref name=\"Merrion Street 2011\" />) is an Irish judge who is currently a Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejournal.ie/ruth-morrissey-appeal-4685421-Jun2019/|title='She wants it to be over': Ruth Morrissey 'very upset' over State move to appeal CervicalCheck case|last=Hennessy|first=Michelle|website=TheJournal.ie|language=en|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/ruth-morrissey-feels-powerless-as-2-1m-cancer-award-appealed-38224604.html|title=Ruth Morrissey feels 'powerless' as \u20ac2.1m cancer award appealed|website=Independent.ie|language=en|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nCross attended [[Gonzaga College]], [[University College Dublin]] and the [[King's Inns]]. He served as Auditor of the [[Literary and Historical Society (University College Dublin)|UCD L&H]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Gonzaga Record 1985 |url=http://www.gonzagaarchive.ie/archive/1985/files/basic-html/page77.html |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref> He became a barrister in 1975 and a senior counsel in 1997.<ref name=\"Merrion Street 2011\">{{cite web |title=Appointments to the High Court |url=https://merrionstreet.ie/en/News-Room/News/appointments-to-the-high-court.html |publisher=Irish Government News Service |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref> He has represented the [[Attorney General of Ireland]], the Residential Institutions Redress Board and [[Our Lady's Children's Hospital, Crumlin]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Challenge on \u00a3475,000 from Christian Brothers site |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/challenge-on-475-000-from-christian-brothers-site-1.339976 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=1 December 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Board's refusal of application challenged |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/board-s-refusal-of-application-challenged-1.785668 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=17 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnellan |first1=Eithne |title=\u00d7 Doctors cleared as inquiry into wrong kidney's removal ends |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/doctors-cleared-as-inquiry-into-wrong-kidney-s-removal-ends-1.646580 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=4 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Judicial career ==\nCross was appointed to the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] in October 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two new High Court judges to fill vacancies |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/two-new-high-court-judges-to-fill-vacancies-26785369.html |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=Irish Independent |date=25 October 2011}}</ref> He is in charge of the personal injuries list for the High Court.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Healy |first1=Tim |title='People may die before cancer misdiagnosis cases are heard' |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/people-may-die-before-cancer-misdiagnosis-cases-are-heard-37580537.html |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=Irish Independent |date=30 November 2018}}</ref> He presided over ''Morrissey v [[Health Service Executive]]'' which arose out of the [[2018 CervicalCheck cancer scandal]]. He held that [[Screening (medicine)|screeners]] must have \"absolute confidence\" before definitively ruling out a health condition in a screening test.<ref>{{cite court|litigants=Morrissey v Health Service Executive & ors|opinion=[2019] IEHC 268|pinpoint=|court=High Court|date=3 May 2019|url=https://www.bailii.org/ie/cases/IEHC/2019/H268.html\n}}</ref> This will be subject to an appeal to the [[Supreme Court of Ireland]] due to the standard of confidence he applied.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cullen |first1=Paul |title=Cancer screening: Claims body says appeal will not affect Ruth Morrissey\u2019s \u20ac2.1m award |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/cancer-screening-claims-body-says-appeal-will-not-affect-ruth-morrissey-s-2-1m-award-1.3928742 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=18 June 2019}}</ref> Cross criticised the response of some doctors to his decision, calling some commentary \"hysterical\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Keena |first1=Colm |title=Judge criticises medical profession for commenting on his ruling |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/judge-criticises-medical-profession-for-commenting-on-his-ruling-1.3888117 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe served as Chairperson of the [[Referendum Commission]] for two concurrent referendums in 2015, the successful [[Thirty-fourth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|34th Amendment]] and unsuccessful [[Thirty-fifth Amendment of the Constitution Bill 2015|35th Amendment Bill 2015]] to the [[Constitution of Ireland|Constitution]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Minister Kelly establishes Referendum Commissions |url=https://www.housing.gov.ie/local-government/voting/referendum-commission/minister-kelly-establishes-referendum-commissions |publisher=Department of the Environment, Community and Local Government |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2020, Cross is the Judge in Charge of the Personal Injuries List.<ref>{{cite web |title=General Notices: 12 February 2020 - HC Judges Hilary '20 |url=http://legaldiary.courts.ie/legaldiary.nsf/general-notices/3ac2b7ee81befa0c8025850c00438620?OpenDocument |publisher=Courts.ie |accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is married to Alison Lindsay.<ref name=\"Independent 2011\">{{cite news |title=The two men now heading for High Court ... |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/the-two-men-now-heading-for-high-court--26781412.html |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=Irish Independent |date=13 October 2011}}</ref> Lindsay is a retired judge of the [[Circuit Court (Ireland)|Circuit Court]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tributes as Circuit Court\u2019s Judge Alison Lindsay retires |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/courts/circuit-court/tributes-as-circuit-court-s-judge-alison-lindsay-retires-1.2739146 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cross, Kevin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:High Court judges (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Chairpersons of the Referendum Commission]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish barrister, High Court judge since 2011}}\n{{Infobox judge\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable|The Hon. Mr. Justice]]\n| name             = Kevin Cross\n| image            =\n| office           = Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]]\n| term_start       = 24 October 2011\n| term_end         = \n| nominator        = [[Government of the 31st D\u00e1il|Government of Ireland]]\n| appointer        = [[Mary McAleese]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth year and age|1951}}\n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party            = \n| spouse           = Alison Lindsay\n| children         =\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = {{Ubl|[[University College Dublin]]|[[King's Inns]]}}\n| signature        = \n|}}\n\n'''Kevin Cross''' (born 1951<ref name=\"Merrion Street 2011\" />) is an Irish judge who is currently a Judge of the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejournal.ie/ruth-morrissey-appeal-4685421-Jun2019/|title='She wants it to be over': Ruth Morrissey 'very upset' over State move to appeal CervicalCheck case|last=Hennessy|first=Michelle|website=TheJournal.ie|language=en|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/ruth-morrissey-feels-powerless-as-2-1m-cancer-award-appealed-38224604.html|title=Ruth Morrissey feels 'powerless' as \u20ac2.1m cancer award appealed|website=Independent.ie|language=en|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nCross attended [[Gonzaga College]], [[University College Dublin]] and the [[King's Inns]]. He served as Auditor of the [[Literary and Historical Society (University College Dublin)|UCD L&H]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Gonzaga Record 1985 |url=http://www.gonzagaarchive.ie/archive/1985/files/basic-html/page77.html |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref> He became a barrister in 1975 and a senior counsel in 1997.<ref name=\"Merrion Street 2011\">{{cite web |title=Appointments to the High Court |url=https://merrionstreet.ie/en/News-Room/News/appointments-to-the-high-court.html |publisher=Irish Government News Service |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref> He has represented the [[Attorney General of Ireland]], the Residential Institutions Redress Board and [[Our Lady's Children's Hospital, Crumlin]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Challenge on \u00a3475,000 from Christian Brothers site |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/challenge-on-475-000-from-christian-brothers-site-1.339976 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=1 December 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Board's refusal of application challenged |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/board-s-refusal-of-application-challenged-1.785668 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=17 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Donnellan |first1=Eithne |title=\u00d7 Doctors cleared as inquiry into wrong kidney's removal ends |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/doctors-cleared-as-inquiry-into-wrong-kidney-s-removal-ends-1.646580 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=4 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Judicial career ==\nCross was appointed to the [[High Court (Ireland)|High Court]] in October 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=Two new High Court judges to fill vacancies |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/two-new-high-court-judges-to-fill-vacancies-26785369.html |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=Irish Independent |date=25 October 2011}}</ref> He is in charge of the personal injuries list for the High Court.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Healy |first1=Tim |title='People may die before cancer misdiagnosis cases are heard' |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/courts/people-may-die-before-cancer-misdiagnosis-cases-are-heard-37580537.html |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=Irish Independent |date=30 November 2018}}</ref> He presided over ''Morrissey v [[Health Service Executive]]'' which arose out of the [[2018 CervicalCheck cancer controversy]]. He held that [[Screening (medicine)|screeners]] must have \"absolute confidence\" before definitively ruling out a health condition in a screening test.<ref>{{cite court|litigants=Morrissey v Health Service Executive & ors|opinion=[2019] IEHC 268|pinpoint=|court=High Court|date=3 May 2019|url=https://www.bailii.org/ie/cases/IEHC/2019/H268.html\n}}</ref> This will be subject to an appeal to the [[Supreme Court of Ireland]] due to the standard of confidence he applied.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cullen |first1=Paul |title=Cancer screening: Claims body says appeal will not affect Ruth Morrissey\u2019s \u20ac2.1m award |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/health/cancer-screening-claims-body-says-appeal-will-not-affect-ruth-morrissey-s-2-1m-award-1.3928742 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=18 June 2019}}</ref> Cross criticised the response of some doctors to his decision, calling some commentary \"hysterical\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Keena |first1=Colm |title=Judge criticises medical profession for commenting on his ruling |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/judge-criticises-medical-profession-for-commenting-on-his-ruling-1.3888117 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe served as Chairperson of the [[Referendum Commission]] for two concurrent referendums in 2015, the successful [[Thirty-fourth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|34th Amendment]] and unsuccessful [[Thirty-fifth Amendment of the Constitution Bill 2015|35th Amendment Bill 2015]] to the [[Constitution of Ireland|Constitution]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Minister Kelly establishes Referendum Commissions |url=https://www.housing.gov.ie/local-government/voting/referendum-commission/minister-kelly-establishes-referendum-commissions |publisher=Department of the Environment, Community and Local Government |accessdate=26 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2020, Cross is the Judge in Charge of the Personal Injuries List.<ref>{{cite web |title=General Notices: 12 February 2020 - HC Judges Hilary '20 |url=http://legaldiary.courts.ie/legaldiary.nsf/general-notices/3ac2b7ee81befa0c8025850c00438620?OpenDocument |publisher=Courts.ie |accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe is married to Alison Lindsay.<ref name=\"Independent 2011\">{{cite news |title=The two men now heading for High Court ... |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/the-two-men-now-heading-for-high-court--26781412.html |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=Irish Independent |date=13 October 2011}}</ref> Lindsay is a retired judge of the [[Circuit Court (Ireland)|Circuit Court]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tributes as Circuit Court\u2019s Judge Alison Lindsay retires |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/crime-and-law/courts/circuit-court/tributes-as-circuit-court-s-judge-alison-lindsay-retires-1.2739146 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cross, Kevin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:High Court judges (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Chairpersons of the Referendum Commission]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's Inns]]\n", "name_user": "Bygmester", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kevin_Cross"}
